SIMPLE: hear
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hear
<hw>Hear</hw> <pr>(h⟦emac⟧r)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Heard</conjf> <pr>(h⟦etil⟧rd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Hearing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>heren</ets>,
AS,. <ets>hi⟦eacute⟧ran</ets>, <ets>h⟦ymac⟧ran</ets>,
<ets>h⟦emac⟧ran</ets>; akin to OS. <ets>h⟦omac⟧rian</ets>, OFries.
<ets>hera</ets>, <ets>hora</ets>, D. <ets>hooren</ets>, OHG.
<ets>h⟦omac⟧ren</ets>, G. <ets>h⟦oum⟧ren</ets>, Icel. <ets>heyra</ets>,
Sw. <ets>h⟦oum⟧ra</ets>, Dan. <ets>hore</ets>, Goth. <ets>hausjan</ets>,
and perh. to Gr. <grk>'akoy`ein</grk>, E. <ets>acoustic</ets>. Cf.
<er>Hark</er>, <er>Hearken</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To perceive by
the ear; to apprehend or take cognizance of by the ear; <as>as, to
<ex>hear</ex> sounds; to <ex>hear</ex> a voice; to <ex>hear</ex> one
call.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lay thine ear close to the ground, and list if thou canst
<qex>hear</qex> the tread of travelers.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had been <qex>heard</qex> to utter an ominous growl.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To give audience or attention to; to listen to; to
heed; to accept the doctrines or advice of; to obey; to examine; to try
in a judicial court; <as>as, to <ex>hear</ex> a recitation; to
<ex>hear</ex> a class; the case will be <ex>heard</ex>
to-morrow.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To attend, or be present at, as hearer or worshiper;
<as>as, to <ex>hear</ex> a concert; to <ex>hear</ex>
Mass.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To give attention to as a teacher or
judge.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thy matters are good and right, but there is no man deputed of the
king to <qex>hear</qex> thee.</q> <rj><qau>2 Sam. xv. 3.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I beseech your honor to <qex>hear</qex> me one single word.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To accede to the demand or wishes of; to listen to
and answer favorably; to favor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I love the Lord, because he hath <qex>heard</qex> my voice.</q>
<rj><qau>Ps. cxvi. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They think that they shall be <qex>heard</qex> for their much
speaking.</q> <rj><qau>Matt. vi. 7.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Hear him</b></col>. <cd>See Remark, under <er>Hear</er>,
<pos>v. i.</pos></cd> -- <col><b>To hear a bird sing</b></col>, <cd>to
receive private communication.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>
<au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>To hear say</b></col>, <cd>to hear one say; to
learn by common report; to receive by rumor.</cd>
<mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hear</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hear
<hw>Hear</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To have the sense or
faculty of perceiving sound.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>hearing</xex>
ear.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Prov. xx. 12.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To use the power of perceiving sound; to perceive or
apprehend by the ear; to attend; to listen.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So spake our mother Eve, and Adam <qex>heard</qex>,⟦br⟧
Well pleased, but answered not.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be informed by oral communication; to be told; to
receive information by report or by letter.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have <qex>heard</qex>, sir, of such a man.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I must <qex>hear</qex> from thee every day in the hour.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To hear ill</b></col>, <cd>to be blamed.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
<q>Not only within his own camp, but also now at Rome, he <qex>heard
ill</qex> for his temporizing and slow proceedings.</q>
<rj><qau>Holland.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
⟦br⟧
-- <col><b>To hear well</b></col>, <cd>to be praised.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Hear</xex>, or <xex>Hear him</xex>, is often used
in the imperative, especially in the course of a speech in English
assemblies, to call attention to the words of the speaker.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Hear him</qex>, . . . a cry indicative, according to the
tone, of admiration, acquiescence, indignation, or derision.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>hearable</ent>⟦br⟧
